<HL> Business Brief:
Caesars World Inc.</HL>
<DD> 10/28/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> CAW
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM) </IN>
<TEXT>
   Martin T. Sosnoff said he lowered his stake in Caesars World Inc. to 4.4% of the common shares outstanding. 
The New York investor has held as much as 16% of the hotel and casino company. 

   In a Securities and Exchange Commission filing, Mr. Sosnoff said he sold 301,900 Caesars World common shares Monday for $13.50 to $14.50 each. 
After the sales, Mr. Sosnoff held 1,072,900 Caesars common shares, the filing said. 

   Mr. Sosnoff acquired his Caesars holdings between May and September of 1986 for $16.51 to $20.38 a share. 

   Yesterday, in composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Caesars common closed at $13.375 a share, off 12.5 cents. 
The company has more than 24 million common shares outstanding. 

   In Los Angeles, officials of Caesars declined to comment on Mr. Sosnoff's SEC filing. 
Mr. Sosnoff couldn't be reached. 

   Earlier this year, Caesars devised a recapitalization plan to fend off an unwanted takeover bid from Mr. Sosnoff. 
Later, the company dropped the plan in favor of a stock buy-back and Mr. Sosnoff began selling his stake. 

